<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This species is found in the mesopelagic (500-1,000 m depth) and bathypelagic zones (1,000-2,000 m depth) of the Pacific, Indian and Atlantic Oceans (
<bibRefCitation author="Pierrot-Bults, AC" editor="Bone, Q" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Science Publications, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="86 - 116" refId="B70" refString="Pierrot-Bults, AC, Nair, VR, 1991. Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha. In: Bone, Q, Kapp, H, Pierrot-Bults, AC, Eds., The Biology of the Chaetognaths. Oxford Science Publications, New York: 86 - 116" title="Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha." volumeTitle="The Biology of the Chaetognaths." year="1991">Pierrot-Bults and Nair 1991</bibRefCitation>
) and the Tosa Bay in Japan (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" author="Ohnishi, T" journalOrPublisher="Plankton &amp; Benthos Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="176 - 187" refId="B59" refString="Ohnishi, T, Ueda, H, Kuroda, K, 2014. Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan. Plankton &amp; Benthos Research 9 (3): 176 - 187, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" title="Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan." url="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" volume="9" year="2014">Ohnishi et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, it was distributed in the epipelagic zone (40-70 m depth) of the Korea Strait (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Sampling stations in Korean waters. Empty circles, sampling stations; filled circles, the stations where the chaetognaths were secured." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.80184.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704185" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">1</figureCitation>
, station KS06).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This species has a high prevalence in warm waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Park, JS" journalOrPublisher="The Korean Society of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B61" refString="Park, JS, 1970. The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." title="The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." year="1970">Park 1970</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, specimens collected around Jeju Island were mainly distributed at water depths&gt; 50 m. The temperature range in the sampling stations was 16.47-21.34 °C and the salinity range was 34.17-34.52 psu.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
In Korean specimens, the position and length of the fins, distance between the anterior and posterior fins and shape of the seminal vesicles were morphologically consistent with the previous records of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Krohn" baseAuthorityYear="1853" class="Sagittoidea" family="Sagittidae" genus="Pseudosagitta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudosagitta lyra" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chaetognatha" rank="species" species="lyra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Pseudosagitta lyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarino, A" journalOrPublisher="University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B4" refString="Alvarino, A, 1967. The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959-1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4). University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" title="The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959 - 1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4)." year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Alvariño">Alvarino</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Michel, HB" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin - United States National Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B49" refString="Michel, HB, 1984. Chaetognatha of the Caribbean Sea and adjacent areas (Vol. 15). National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. Technical Report of National Marine Fisheries Service 15: e25." title="Chaetognatha of the Caribbean Sea and adjacent areas (Vol. 15). National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. Technical Report of National Marine Fisheries Service 15: e 25." year="1984">Michel 1984</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lutschinger, S" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Plankton Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B45" refString="Lutschinger, S, 1993. The marine fauna of New Zealand: Chaetognatha (arrow worms). New Zealand Oceanographic Institute Memoir 101." title="The marine fauna of New Zealand: Chaetognatha (arrow worms). New Zealand Oceanographic Institute Memoir 101." year="1993">Lutschinger 1993</bibRefCitation>
). As one of the larger species of arrow worm, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. lyra" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="lyra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">P. lyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reaches a maximum size of 42 mm (
<bibRefCitation author="Michel, HB" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin - United States National Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B49" refString="Michel, HB, 1984. Chaetognatha of the Caribbean Sea and adjacent areas (Vol. 15). National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. Technical Report of National Marine Fisheries Service 15: e25." title="Chaetognatha of the Caribbean Sea and adjacent areas (Vol. 15). National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. Technical Report of National Marine Fisheries Service 15: e 25." year="1984">Michel 1984</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lutschinger, S" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Plankton Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B45" refString="Lutschinger, S, 1993. The marine fauna of New Zealand: Chaetognatha (arrow worms). New Zealand Oceanographic Institute Memoir 101." title="The marine fauna of New Zealand: Chaetognatha (arrow worms). New Zealand Oceanographic Institute Memoir 101." year="1993">Lutschinger 1993</bibRefCitation>
). However, the largest of the Korean specimens collected in this study was 60 mm in length. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alvarino" baseAuthorityYear="1962" class="Sagittoidea" family="Sagittidae" genus="Pseudosagitta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudosagitta scrippsae" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chaetognatha" rank="species" species="scrippsae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Pseudosagitta scrippsae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily confused with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. lyra" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="lyra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">P. lyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with similar size and position and shape of the fins and seminal vesicles. However, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. scrippsae" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="scrippsae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">P. scrippsae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated by the presence of a distinct collarette around the neck (
<bibRefCitation author="Chihara, M" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Indiana Academy of Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B15" refString="Chihara, M, Murano, M, 1997. An Illustrated Guide to Marine Plankton in Japan. Tokai University Press, 1571 pp." title="An Illustrated Guide to Marine Plankton in Japan. Tokai University Press, 1571 pp." year="1997">Chihara and Murano 1997</bibRefCitation>
). No specific pattern was observed through CBE staining on the body surface.
</paragraph>
